<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-302-796  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 302 796.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 2 1990 n294 p13(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It adds up: ATandamp;T is still dominant. (AT and T's bid for fewerregulatory restrictions) (Perspective) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilkens, Roy A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>While AT and T claims that it is not a dominant carrier and thatrestrictions resulting from the 1984 divestiture ruling should bealleviated by the FCC, the statistics indicate otherwise.andO;Although AT and T has lost market share since divestiture, itsearnings and stock price have nearly doubled.andP;  In 1989, thistranslated into a 70 percent share of the long distance market, 70percent of the business market, 75 percent of the residentialmarket and over 90 percent of international traffic.andP;  This is notto mention the fact that AT and T wrote off $6 billion in obsoleteequipment in 1988 and invested $4 billion in capital expendituresin 1989.andP;  In fact, its advertising budget for 1989, $775 million,was more than the $500 million that other communication serviceproviders spent in combined capital investments.andP;  The long rangeinterests of the consumer will best be served by a competitivemarket.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (rules and regulations).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Communications Service SuppliersCommunications ManagementDominationLegal IssuesCompetitionProfitInvestmentsDeregulation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>